[normal]5.7
[normal]We’ve won national customer service awards demonstrating how passionate we are about our service
[normal] to vulnerable clients in TA
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] Financially it’s becoming more difficult to provide the service across all 18 areas. The changes to housing costs within the wel
[normal]fare system remain a huge concern to the future of us being able to house vulnerable homeless clients.
[normal]The Government are introducing direct payments within universal credit. The main aim is to empower residents to manage money, ensuring they understand ho
[normal]w working families budget when receiving a monthly salary. The Government tell us this will be a cost neutral exercise for them. What they haven’t considered is the full impact direct payments will have. Even though Government recognise Universal Credit mu
[normal]st be designed to protect the financial position of landlords, d
[normal]irect payment to tenants still means landlords will have to take unacceptable risks on collecting rent. Many landlords will not take that risk, leading to less supply in the private rented 
[normal]sec
[normal]tor and a higher B&amp;B bill/ cost to public purse. 
[normal]Concern has already been stressed by many landlords that low income or vulnerable families will not pay rent.
[normal] No families in temporary accommodation have been included in the UC pilots.
[normal] If this happens ultimately these families will end up being evicted. As local authorities have a duty to find shelter for homeless families, their only option will be to place them in unsuitable and expensive B&amp;B. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Many aspects of Welfare reform make lea
[normal]sing temporary accommodation from the private sector no longer a financial viable option for many registered social landlords. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The supply of good quality temporary accommodation is reducing, especially in London &amp; the South where there’s a buoyant private
[normal] rental market. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The
[normal] direct payment element 
[normal]will not make 
[normal]the welfare reform policy cost neutral. Instead it will increase LA spend through 
[normal]Discretionary Housing Payments (
[normal]DHP
[normal]) 
[normal]or the general fund.
[normal] 
[normal]If tenants do not pay their rent registered social landlo
[normal]rds will incur higher bad debt. This will ultimately affect our credit scoring and ability to borrow/self fund in an environment where grant funding to build new affordable homes is 
[normal]disappearing. The
[normal] end result is registered social landlords will not build
[normal] much needed new homes, holding back the recovery of the economy even further.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We want to continue to provide this service which our L
[normal]A
[normal] partners value. But proposed changes to how TA is funded are making it increasingly difficult for us to retain lease
[normal]s and continue to provide this service. Here’s a summary of the issues:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]All these
[normal] issues ultimately point to an increased spend for the public purse on inappropriate bed and bedfast for vulnerable families.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.0[bold]&#xa0;[bold]6.1
[normal]Innovation to support discharge of duty into PRS[bold]&#xa0;[bold]The localism act allows local authorities to discharge the duty of homelessness into the private rented sector. Again we completely support this where families can support themselves. But from our experience there are many families who require 
[normal]a higher lev
[normal]el of management to help them sustain tenancies. 
[normal]Experience also tells us many landlords require extra support to manage vulnerable client groups. Its no secret many private landlords already only accept working families.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.
[normal]2
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.3
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We’ve been working with one LA to provide good quality housing from the private sector to allow them to discharge duty of homeless clients on 12 month assured short hold tenancies. The LA 
[normal]supports
[normal] us financially to manage the tenant, without financial detr
[normal]iment to the landlord.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]From year 2 the tenant has received enough support to know how to sustain their tenancy. The LA 
[normal]removes
[normal] financial support and we manage the letting as a private let with the owner. This removes the hassle for the landlord. Removes t
[normal]he problem of failing tenancies and repeated homelessness and provides a stable long term home for a family.
